<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-03-10T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-03-10T22:00:00-05:00" n="498" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d498">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/1491: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Canton (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BJW1" type="from">Ballantine</persName>)
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-11T11:00:00+08:00">March 11, 1932—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 12—7:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>My February 26, 4 p.m.<note n="17" xml:id="d498fn17">Not printed.</note>
                            I have been informed by the military authorities that on account of the
                            approach of the Kwantung forces <pb facs="0579" n="481" xml:id="pg_481"/> the Communists have raised the siege of Kanchow, and that while
                            Americans there are presumably safe it will be impossible to confirm
                            this until the Kwantung forces reach there.</p>
                        <p>Legation, Nanking, Hankow and Department informed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BJW1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Ballantine</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>